<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881026-0103 </DOCNO><HL> World Bank Clears Loans for 3 Countries </HL><SO> </SO><CO> AFRIC FREST </CO><IN> BNK MON </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The World Bank cleared $531.6 million in loans to Nigeria, India and Zaire to support the economic development of those nations.    A $270 million credit to Nigeria will be used to help set up small and medium-sized business ventures and finance imports of equipment for factories, mining operations and other enterprises.    India will get two loans totaling $250 million from the World Bank and its affiliate, the International Development Association, to upgrade 2,300 kilometers of roads.    Zaire will get an $11.6 million IDA credit to improve the efficiency of government ministries responsible for planning agricultural-development projects.    The World Bank credits will be at variable interest rates, linked to the bank's own borrowing costs. The IDA credits will be interest-free except for administrative fees. </TEXT></DOC>